      "mainEntity": [
        { "@type":"Question","name":"What electronics can be recycled in Kochi?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"EWaste Kochi accepts all categories of electronics for recycling: laptops, desktops, servers, monitors (CRT and LCD), printers, MFPs, smartphones, tablets, hard drives, SSDs, batteries (lithium-ion, lead-acid, NiMH), networking equipment, UPS systems, projectors, TVs, air conditioners, washing machines, refrigerators, and all other electrical and electronic equipment covered under E-Waste Rules 2022. Industrial e-waste and full data centre decommissions are also accepted."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"Is electronics recycling free in Kochi?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. EWaste Kochi offers free drop-off at our Thrippunithura facility for any quantity of electronics. Free door-to-door pickup is available for corporate clients with 10 or more devices anywhere in Kochi and Ernakulam. Residential clients can also request free pickup for large quantities (TVs, refrigerators, ACs, etc.). There is no charge for standard electronics recycling — we recover value from materials."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"What is zero-landfill electronics recycling?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Zero-landfill recycling means 100% of the electronics we collect are diverted from landfill. Every material stream is processed — metals (ferrous, non-ferrous, precious), plastics (sorted by polymer type), glass (CRT glass, LCD panels), and rare earth elements. Nothing is dumped in a landfill or sent to illegal burning sites. EWaste Kochi has maintained a zero-landfill certification continuously since 2018, audited annually by KSPCB."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"How does electronics recycling protect the environment in Kochi?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Electronics contain toxic materials — lead (CRT glass), mercury (LCD backlights), cadmium (rechargeable batteries), chromium, and brominated flame retardants. When disposed of in landfills or burned by informal scrap dealers, these toxins leach into Kerala's groundwater and soil, affecting communities near Eloor, Kalamassery, and the Periyar river basin. Certified recycling at EWaste Kochi extracts these toxins safely and neutralizes them, while recovering valuable materials that would otherwise be mined at high environmental cost."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"What happens to my old laptop when I send it for recycling in Kochi?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"When you send a laptop to EWaste Kochi, it goes through a structured process: (1) Data destruction — NIST 800-88 certified wiping or physical drive shredding; (2) Assessment — is the device resaleable after refurbishment? (3) If yes, it enters our refurbishment and remarketing stream, extending its useful life; (4) If not, it is fully disassembled — screen panels separated, battery removed, circuit boards extracted, aluminum chassis separated; (5) Each material stream is processed separately for maximum material recovery."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"Do you recycle CRT monitors in Kochi?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. EWaste Kochi is one of the few certified facilities in Kerala equipped to handle CRT (cathode ray tube) monitors safely. CRT monitors contain 2–8 pounds of lead oxide per unit in the glass funnel — making them one of the most hazardous e-waste streams. Our process involves mechanical shearing of the leaded funnel glass from the front panel glass, under HEPA-filtered negative pressure to prevent lead dust escape. The lead glass is then sent to specialized smelters for safe lead recovery."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"How is gold recovered from circuit boards in Kochi?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Circuit boards contain trace quantities of gold, silver, palladium, and copper on contact points, connectors, and chip leads. At scale (thousands of boards), this represents significant recovery value. EWaste Kochi uses a combination of mechanical shredding, eddy current separation, and hydrometallurgical processing to separate and concentrate precious metals from board fragments. The recovered metals are certified and sold to refinery partners. This is the foundation of the circular economy — recovering urban ore rather than extracting new material from the earth."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"Is it mandatory to recycle electronics in Kerala?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. Under the E-Waste (Management) Rules 2022, all businesses and institutions in India including Kerala must channel electronic waste through KSPCB/CPCB-authorized recyclers. Individuals are also expected to deposit e-waste at designated collection centres rather than disposing of it in regular waste streams. Businesses that fail to comply risk fines and penalties from the Kerala State Pollution Control Board. Additionally, the DPDP Act 2023 makes certified data destruction mandatory for businesses disposing of data-bearing devices."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"What is the circular economy and how does EWaste Kochi contribute?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The circular economy is a regenerative economic model where materials are kept in use for as long as possible, waste is minimized, and resources are recovered and reintroduced into the production cycle. EWaste Kochi contributes by: (1) Refurbishing and remarketing functional devices, extending product life; (2) Recovering precious metals (gold, silver, copper, palladium) from circuit boards for reuse in new electronics manufacturing; (3) Recovering aluminum, steel, and other metals for industrial reuse; (4) Processing plastics for polymer recycling; (5) Ensuring zero material goes to landfill, closing the material loop."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"Can you recycle lithium-ion batteries from electric vehicles in Kochi?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. EWaste Kochi handles lithium-ion batteries from all sources — laptops, smartphones, electric scooters, and electric vehicles. EV battery recycling requires specialized handling: batteries must be fully discharged before processing, thermal runaway risks must be managed, and the valuable lithium, cobalt, nickel, and manganese must be safely extracted. Our facility uses inert-environment processing to safely dismantle lithium battery packs. This is increasingly important as Kerala's EV adoption grows rapidly."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"How do you recycle LCD and LED monitors in Kochi?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"LCD and LED monitors contain several material streams that require separation: the aluminum or plastic housing is separated and recycled; the glass panel (containing indium) is processed; the CCFL backlights in older LCDs contain mercury and require specialized mercury-safe processing; LED backlights are simpler but still require separation. The electronics inside (PSU board, T-con board, inverter) are processed as circuit boards for precious metal recovery. Each layer requires specialized handling to achieve true zero-landfill."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"What happens to plastic from recycled electronics?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Electronics plastics are sorted by polymer type — ABS (acrylonitrile butadiene styrene, most common in electronics), polycarbonate, HIPS, and polypropylene. Sorting is critical because mixed plastics have little recycling value. EWaste Kochi uses density separation and near-infrared (NIR) sorting to separate polymer types. The sorted plastics are then granulated and sold to plastic compounders who produce new plastic products. Bromine-containing flame retardant plastics require specialized treatment due to potential dioxin generation during processing."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"What certifications does EWaste Kochi hold for electronics recycling?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"EWaste Kochi holds: KSPCB (Kerala State Pollution Control Board) authorization for e-waste collection and processing; EPR (Extended Producer Responsibility) registration under E-Waste Rules 2022; CPCB (Central Pollution Control Board) registered facility; ISO 27001-aligned data destruction processes; NIST 800-88 and DoD 5220.22-M data destruction certification; R2 (Responsible Recycling) aligned practices. We maintain all certifications current and can provide copies for your compliance records."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"What is EPR (Extended Producer Responsibility) in e-waste?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"EPR (Extended Producer Responsibility) is a policy principle embedded in India's E-Waste Rules 2022 that holds electronics producers legally responsible for the end-of-life management of their products. Under EPR, manufacturers like Samsung, HP, Dell, and Apple must meet collection and recycling targets for their devices sold in India, typically working through authorized recycling partners. EWaste Kochi is an EPR-registered collection and processing partner, meaning devices recycled through us count toward producers' EPR targets."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"How quickly can e-waste be picked up for recycling in Kochi?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"EWaste Kochi offers same-day and next-day pickup across all Kochi and Ernakulam zones. For urgent corporate requirements at Infopark, Smart City, or Kakkanad, pickup is often possible within 2–4 hours of your call. We operate 24/7 including weekends and public holidays. Walk-in drop-off at our Thrippunithura facility is welcome anytime — no appointment needed."}},
        { "@type":"Question","name":"Can I get an environmental impact certificate for corporate CSR reporting?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. EWaste Kochi provides an Environmental Impact Certificate with qualifying recycling projects. This document details: total weight of electronics recycled (in kg/tonnes); material recovery breakdown by category (metals, plastics, glass, precious metals); carbon footprint avoided versus landfill disposal; equivalent trees saved metric; and KSPCB authorization references. This is ideal for BRSR (Business Responsibility and Sustainability Reporting) filings, corporate CSR reports, ESG disclosures, and GHG inventories."}}
